reviewText: Written and directed by Paul Andrew Williams who wrote the 2008 film 'The Children'. The opening long time shot of the pot of vegetables boiling is a wonderful start. The acting of the adult parents in this film is a joy to watch. The couple played by Rachel Blake and Tom Butcher is pure excellent casting. They really put to shame other actors that we see regularly in television and film.For realism and quality; talent is crucial in a film like this. The camerawork at the beginning, before the door bell rings, reminded me of Kubrick's work where the camera stays rolling in a single position. There is another shot that comes to mind in this film when a youth is going through a DVD collection and you only see his back. It's just a single shot, but very powerful, especially with the classical piano music playing. Everything about the start to this film is terrific.There is a good story here, I knew absolutely nothing about this feature and I was loving it up until the gang arrive. There is a big problem for me with this film, let me explain: You've got a good creative director who wrote and directed...that box is Ticked. Good  production...Tick. Great story and two experienced adult actors ...Tick, as mentioned earlier. But the young ring leader of the gang played by Jumayn Hunter is not believable enough. Ashley Chin, one of the gang members would have been better cast as the leader. If they swapped their roles over, the film would have been creatively correct.The other person I would have considered in this nasty gang leader role would have been Ben Drew, the lead singer from UK band 'Plan B'. If you have seen him in `Harry Brown' you'll know why. I'm sure this film would work well as it is for some of you. However, I believe a home invasion film needs a character or characters that stay with you afterwards for whatever reason. For example the four distinct droogs in `A Clockwork Orange', the two strangers in `Funny Games', the vampire leader played by Danny Houston in the awesome '30 Days of Night'....you see where I'm going with this.The other alternative for director / writer Paul Andrew Williams could have been an older actor to play the ring leader...As the film is right now, you have a young gang that is one singular beast. It would have been more realistic and clever if the young gang had very different personalities, but shared the same intention. When young female characters are later introduced into the story, again it was difficult to suspend belief because their characters were so confident. In any story you need characters to react differently to what's happening around them. They can't all act like confident wannabe gangsters, you need more layers than that.I noticed far too many close up shots of faces in this film. It needed variety, like the distance shots that were included at the beginning. It's not major, but it would have given the film another dimension. My final problem, which I've mentioned when reviewing `Funny Games' is this: When you watch a home invasion film, I have yet to see victims attempt to fight back - characters seem to give up straight away. I wish the mother in 'Cherry Tree Lane' headbutted the ring leader because she was sat face to face on the sofa for long enough, I'm not saying I want a happy ending or she escapes, it would demonstrate a real sense of a mothers survival instinct.In real life even the gentle of us can show extreme courage or physical strength when unexpected horrific events suddenly happen.I hope those of you who are in the profession understand that if you get funding and are fortunate to turn your story into a creative piece of work, just make bloody sure you get the casting right, go with your instinct and make sure your chosen actors put the work in with each other beforehand, so you believe the relationships on screen.  To balance things out a bit I did like some footage and the parent characters. It's not awful and it is pretty extreme to view at times. It has its place in the genre, but it could have been much better.... perhaps casting young actors in such a demanding film is a very difficult task.'Cherry Tree Lane' is well worth seeing just for the beginning build up and what happens at the end, that's for sure.bleedingcriticbleedingfilms.com

reviewText: A simple night at home turns into a deadly game of survival for Christine and Michael when three of their son's low-life friends hold them hostage while waiting for him to return. Director Paul Andrew Williams of THE COTTAGE fame has digested the works of Wes Craven and Michael Haneke then placed an urban edge on them in the 2010 home invasion Horror story, CHERRY TREE LANE. A strict dichotomy is drawn between Britain's upper and lower classes, where Williams has the chance to explore the mutual exclusivity of each through the microcosm on screen. The same dark humor that we experienced in FUNNY GAMES creeps through these teens' bleak world view as well, proposing a life in which violence and crime have become accepted as a daily occurrence. Where CHERRY TREE LANE falters is in its inability to bring anything new to the table. We have seen this all before, it has simply been reprocessed to fit the current social climate that surrounds Britain's inner city youth. Williams does leave us with a brilliant closing shot, however, and one that intentionally provokes the viewer to choose between giving in to their insatiable blood lust and desire for revenge, or to maintain their last hold on civilization. CHERRY TREE LANE does show a marked improvement in style and form for the director.-Carl ManesI Like Horror Movies

reviewText: Filmmakers love to exploit people's worst fears. Think about all the films made over the years about plane disasters, natural disasters, zombie outbreaks, airborne pathogens, serial killers, and any and everything else released in theaters or on DVD weekly. For some reason, we're all drawn to seeing what might happen in any of these situations and experience them from the outside looking in. "Cherry Tree Lane" gives us a "glass house" view of what many people would consider one of the most frightening horrors they could experience: the home invasion.An ordinary middle-class couple named Christine (Rachel Blake) and Mike (Tom Butcher) arrive at home and settle in for an evening together. Their son, Sebastian (Tom Kane), hasn't arrived yet. You can tell the two have issues between them through awkward talk at the dinner table.The evening takes a turn for the worse when Christine answers a knock at the door and returns to the dining area held captive by a thug with a knife to her throat. The couple soon find themselves bound, gagged, and beaten as their captors await their son's arrival. It seems Sebastian is running with a rough crowd and turned in one of the young delinquent's brothers."Cherry Tree Lane" is a slow-burning and tense movie that does its best to explore every aspect of a home invasion. However, instead of showing you everything, it leaves much to your imagination. It's not worse than seeing horrific actions onscreen, but creates a more stressful viewing experience.Director / writer Paul Andrew Williams definitely knows how to pace a good suspense yarn. This has been referred to as a real-time thriller by some people. Let's just say a lot can happen in 77-minutes. "Cherry Tree Lane" shows audiences that it doesn't take too much time for lives to be destroyed and bad decisions to change the course of one's future forever.Williams does a great job showing how messed up these thugs are throughout the film. One calls their parents and argues with them about a TV show they want recorded. Another one invites their girlfriend over to the scene of the crime to hang out. She brings her friend and a young boy with her. To them, this is just business as usual. It reminded me of how Alex and his droogs acted after a night of ultra-violence in "A Clockwork Orange."Another way of looking at "Cherry Tree Lane" is as a cautionary tale. You never know how your actions are going to affect others. Sebastian's actions caused his parents to come to harm. He not only set himself up to be oppressed, but got others involved as well.Although the movie is Unrated, it features violence, partial nudity, and a whole lot of bad language. This is definitely not for the squeamish. It's also not something you probably want your teenager or young children watching."Cherry Tree Lane" only comes in a regular format DVD edition. There are no special features included in the packaging. It would've been nice to see a "Making of" featurette and get a little background on the project from director / writer Paul Andrew Williams.At first, I felt "Cherry Tree Lane" was a bit slow-moving for my taste. After reflecting on it, I realized that it's actually a well-paced little film that explores an invasion of our privacy and humanity without being too exploitative. Don't get me wrong. It's disturbing and unnerving, but never steps over the line into "torture-porn" territory where a lot of movies like this tend to go.

reviewText: Nothing good to say about this movie except that the low ratings it has are well deserved. The movie starts off with a flourishing couple drinking wine and eating dinner. Then their house is invaded by 2 black hoodlums and a white guy whose there just to be there. The movie has all the stereotypical elements that people fear black men doing to them. Breaking into their home,taking their money,raping their wife, hurting their kids, etc. etc. etc. I have yet to see a movie this insulting,ignorant,ridiculous,and down right disgusting in a long time. Then at the end the husband breaks free and all of a sudden the hoodlums start running away and he ends up catching one of the black guys (of course) and beating them to death (a fantasy). When early on in the movie it shows the same guy and his friends punching the guy in the face, knocking him to the ground and beating the stuffing out of him. It be strange to think that all of sudden now that this same guy is free this group of thugs would fear him and start running away. Wouldn't they just beat him up again for getting free? Any way I'm not sure who would enjoy this movie better yet I just question those who didn't catch how stereotypical this movie was.
summary: If you enjoy racists stereotypes this is your movie!

reviewText: Despite its flaws, CHERRY TREE LANE emerges as a visceral and uncomfortable experience.  It's as senselessly cruel as A CLOCKWORK ORANGE but mercifully shorter.Much of the dialogue is so thickly accented, portions are difficult to comprehend, especially early on.  What gives the film its impact is how angry it makes the viewer and how it makes us cheer when the tables are turned.  The movie's "Will he or won't he" final scene is chilling.  Overall, CHERRY TREE LANE is a disturbing home invasion film.
summary: NO HOME SWEET HOME ON CHERRY TREE LANE

reviewText: Michael (Tom Butcher) and Christine (Rachael Blake) have a strained relationship. He doesn't trust her after she confessed to an indiscretion. They also have an issue with their son Sebastien (Tom Kane) who have been hanging out with the wrong sort. Their conversation is low, so I needed to crank up the volume to hear what they were saying. What was with the still camera in the opening bedroom shot?Soon some of Sebastien's mates break in looking for him in a bad sort of way. This becomes a home break-in film as our gang helps themselves to some cookies, DVDs, and the wife. Things get weird when the gang's girlfriends show up, one of which is dragging along her innocent pre-teen brother.The break-in formula runs its course and rather quickly in this 77 minute film.The acting was alright, the characters needed a little more developing. The home break-in terror was light compared to others in this genre. You might want to go watch "Mother's Day" or "Last House on the Left" again before seeing this one. Not really worth renting.Parental Guide: F-bomb, off screen rape, discreet nudity. Wal Mart $9.96
